svg.desc:
#align: center #title: gitworkflow #spacing: 25 #arrowSize: 2
#.input: fill=#000000 visual=input stroke=#e0e0e0 #.class: body=center title=bold #.note: body=center title=bold visual=note
[Remote Branch Tracking] -- [<input> git merge] --> [Working Directory] [Remote] -- [<input> git fetch] --> [Remote Branch Tracking]
[Remote] -- [<input>git pull] --> [Working Directory] [Remote] <--[<input> git push] -- [Local Repository] <--[<input> git commit] -- [Staging] <-- [<input> git add] -- [Working Directory] [Staging] -- [<input> git reset] --> [Working Directory]
[Remote Branch Tracking] -- [<input>git checkout branch_name] -->[Working Directory]
[Stash] <-- [<input> git stash] -- [Working Directory] [Stash] -- [<input> git stash apply] --> [Working Directory] [Stash] -- [<input> git stash pop] --> [Working Directory]
[Working Directory] -- [<input> git diff > patchfile.patch] --> [<input>Patch file] [Working Directory] <-- [<input> git apply patchfile.patch] -- [<input>Patch file] [Staging] -- [<input>git diff --cached] -->[<input>Patch file]
[<input>git pull| equivalent with: git fetch git merge]
[Working Directory| Refers to the main folder on your computer where you keep all your project files. It's the place where you make changes and edits to your files. ]
[<database>Stash| It is like a secret hiding place where you can temporarily store changes you made to your files without committing them. It's useful when you want to switch to a different branch or work on something else without losing your current changes.]
[<database>Remote|A copy of the repository that is hosted on a different server or location. It serves as a central place where multiple people can collaborate on the same project and exchange changes]
[<database>Local Repository|A special folder where Git stores all the files and the history of changes for a project. It acts as a centralized database that keeps track of every modification made to the project's files over time.]
[Staging|An intermediate step between the working directory and the repository. It's where changes made to files in the working directory are selected and prepared to be included in the next commit]
[Remote Branch Tracking|Allows your local branches to stay in sync with branches on the remote repository. When you clone a remote repository, Git automatically sets up tracking for the remote branches]
[<note>Patch file|A text file that contains the differences between two sets of files. It shows the changes made to the original files and can be used to update or modify those files accordingly.]
